SIMPLE: inheritable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inheritable
<hw>In*her"it*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Capable of being inherited; transmissible or descendible; <as>as,
an <ex>inheritable</ex> estate or title</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Capable of being transmitted from parent to child;
<as>as, <ex>inheritable</ex> qualities or infirmities</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>enheritable</ets>,
<ets>inheritable</ets>.]</ety> <def>Capable of taking by inheritance, or
of receiving by descent; capable of succeeding to, as an heir.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By attainder . . . the blood of the person attainted is so
corrupted as to be rendered no longer <qex>inheritable</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The eldest daughter of the king is also alone
<qex>inheritable</qex> to the crown on failure of issue male.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Inheritable blood</b></col>, <cd>blood or relationship by
which a person becomes qualified to be an heir, or to transmit
possessions by inheritance.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inheritably</ent>⟦br⟧
